	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The FAO highlights escalating food import costs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 May 2008
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The FAO is projecting a 56% increase in the cereal import bill of the world’s poorest countries in 2007/08, on top of the 37% increase that occurred in 2006/07. For low income countries in Africa the increase is likely to be higher at 74% as a result of increasing cereal prices and escalating freight costs. ‘By the end of March prices of wheat and rice were about double their levels of a year earlier’. FAO meanwhile has launched an input supply programme designed to boost local production, this includes initiative sin Burkina Faso, Mauritania, Mozambique and Senegal. Non-cereal food prices are also soaring. This has provoked food riots in a number of ACP countries including: Cameroon, Côte d’Ivoire, Senegal, Burkina Faso, Ethiopia, Madagascar and Haiti. Against this background the FAO has launched an appeal for additional funding to meet the import needs of poor countries.</p><p> According to FAO ‘world cereal production in 2008 is to increase by 2.6% to a record 2,164 million tonnes’. This should ease the tight supply situation and hence price pressures. Nevertheless world cereal stocks are at a 25-year low so prices are likely to remain volatile depending on the evolution of currently planted crops.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> FAO <i>press release</i> April 11th 2008, Rome</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2008/1000826/index.html" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2008/1000826/index.html</a> <br/> </p><p> FAO <i>press release</i>, April 2nd 2008, Rome</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2008/1000823/index.html" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2008/1000823/index.html</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Soaring import bills are leading ACP countries to focus increased policy attention on the promotion of domestic production. However, short-term measures to increase supplies to the domestic market (removal of import duties and imposition of export taxes) can serve to undermine domestic production in the medium to long term. It is in this context that concerns have been expressed about a number of the contentious clauses in the IEPAs and the need for their substantive revision, in order to avoid any disruption of existing domestic policy measures designed to promote domestic food production.</p>
		</div>
		
